    public interface IFIXMessage
extends IFIXMessageSpecifics, ITagValues, IFastDecodableMessage, IFastEncodableMessage
    Interface which must be supported by all message objects processed by Catalys.

    Method Summary:

    • Inherits all the IFIXMessageSpecifics methods - see summary for IFIXMessageSpecifics
    • Inherits all the ITagValues methods - see summary for ITagValues
    • toString(int)

    As of Catalys 2.0 the repeating groups API is deprecated and may be removed completely in a future release. It is recommended that it not be used in client code.

    Specifically, any call to query, retrieve or create a repeating group is considered to activate the API and repeating groups API and potentially cause internal resources to be consumed to house the associated metadata. In order to avoid using the repeating groups API and the associated overhead it is sufficient simply not to attempt to query, retrieve or create any repeating groups via IRepeatingGroupAccessor.

    The recommended alternatives are:

    • When reading a FIX message - iteration via:
      • ITagValueIterableFromTag.iterator() - create a new iterator from the start of the message
      • ITagValueIterableFromTag.iterator(int) - create a new iterator from the specified tag
      • IBindable.isBindable(Object) - test whether an existing iterator is binding to this message
      • IBindable.bind(Object) - bind an existing iterator to this message for iteration from the start of the message
      • ITagValueIteratorBindable.bind(java.util.Iterator, com.camerontec.catalys.util.data.ITagValue) - bind an existing iterator to this message for iteration using the supplied return value buffer
      • ITagValueIteratorBindable.bind(java.util.Iterator, int, com.camerontec.catalys.util.data.ITagValue) - bind an existing iterator to this message for iteration from the specified tag using the supplied return value buffer
    • When writing a FIX message - simply use the ITagValues.addField(com.camerontec.catalys.util.data.ITagValue) family of methods in the appropriate order.

    Adherence to these recommendations is likely to yield far better performance in both cases.

    The ability to bind() an existing iterator to an IFIXMessage instance is designed to be used for garbage free iteration. A typical usage is: 

       // Store iterator as a member variable.
   private ListIterator<ITagValue> iterator;

   ...

   public void onMessage(IFIXMessage message) {
     // Optional - only required if there is a possibility of having to process different instances of IFIXMessage.
     if (!message.isBindable(iterator)) {
       // This is guaranteed to be bindable.
       iterator = message.iterator();
     }

     // Bind the iterator to a message prior to iteration.
     // Note that is is OK for iterator to be null here as the implementation creates a suitable iterator
     // automatically which is stored for later reuse.
     // What is not OK is attempting to bind an iterator obtained from a different IFIXMessage implementation.
     // Iterators can be tested for bindability first via message.isBindable(iterator) to avoid unexpected exceptions.
     iterator = message.bind(iterator);
     while (iterator.hasNext() {
       // Modifying field directly modifies the underlying data, however, may involve garbage creation.
       final ITagValue field = iterator.next();
       // Process field ...
     }
   }

    Depending on the IFIXMessage implementation it may be necessary to use the following bind() variant to guarantee garbage free iteration: 

       // Store iterator and reusable return value buffer a member variables.
   private ListIterator<ITagValue> iterator;
   private ITagValue returnBuffer = new StandardTagValue();

   ...

   public void onMessage(IFIXMessage message) {
     iterator = message.bind(iterator, 0, returnBuffer);
     while (iterator.hasNext() {
       // Here, field is actually returnBuffer used to reference the underlying data. In this case, modifying
       // returnBuffer has no effect on the underlying data but is guaranteed to be garbage free.
       final ITagValue field = iterator.next();
       // Process field ...
     }
   }

    The above iteration methods may continue be used in conjunction with the deprecated repeating groups API, however, as mentioned some performance may be compromised. In addition, the reusable iterator() variants (i.e. those which take another iterator as an argument) guarantee to fallback to the other non reusable variants when the repeating groups API is in use (see above for what this means).

    • Method Detail

      • parseRawInMessage

        void parseRawInMessage(boolean dialectAllowNoLengthOnRawData)
                throws MessageParsingException
        This method will be called prior to accessing the fields of a message constructed from "raw input" (@see #setRawInMessage).

        Note that an implementation is not obliged to fully parse all raw input when this method is called. Some implementations may choose to do parsing on demand - as individual fields are requested. This method is just called as an indication that field access is about to begin. How your implementation reacts to this method is up to you.

        Parameters:
        dialectAllowNoLengthOnRawData - True to indicate that no special treatment is to be given to raw data and their associated length fields (that is, they are expected to conform to regular FIX field content and in particular the data field should not contain FIX SOH), false to treat the data field as opaque and use its preceding length field to determine its length.
        Throws:
        MessageParsingException - If the message is badly formed in some way.

      • toString

        String toString(int format)
        Returns a string representation of the message.

        The string is formatted according to the value of format as follows:

        • FORMAT_SUMMARY - Summary format.
        • FORMAT_SUMMARY_VERBOSE - Summary format but with more details.
        • FORMAT_FULL - Full format.
        • FORMAT_VERBOSE - Full format with tag names instead of values.
        • FORMAT_RAW_IN - Raw input data from which message was constructed.
        • any other value - Summary format.
        Parameters:
        format - Required format of returned String - should take one of the above values.
        Returns:
        String representation of message.

      • isEqualMessage

        boolean isEqualMessage(IFIXMessage other,
                       boolean strictOrder)
        Compares the specified IFIXMessage with this IFIXMessage for equality, i.e. whether their contents and other FIX specific fields are the same.
        Parameters:
        other - IFIXMessage to be compared for equality with this IFIXMessage.
        strictOrder - if true the order of the tags in the message is significant, otherwise this methods returns true even if the tag order is not the same, as long as both messages contain the same tags
        Returns:
        true If the specified IFIXMessage is equal to this IFIXMessage.
